<Author>Chesslover17
<Content>Good hotel - Great location The Hotel Atlas is brand new ... open just 40 days when we checked in (June 11, 2008). The rooms, elevator, and hallways are on the small side, the floors are covered with linoleum, there is a church bell that rings every half hour from 8:00 a.m. until 10:00 p.m. that the sound proofing does not keep out, and it helps if you like orange walls and bedspreads, but these detractions were insignificant relative to the benefits this hotel offered.The bathroom had modern facilities and we found the beds to be very comfortable. The staff speaks several languages including English and were very friendly and helpful. They were very attentive when we couldn't figure out how to work the air conditioner and were happy to give us directions and recommendations of places to go and things to see. The hotel offers breakfast that, considering the price we were paying, was fairly extensive. It consisted of cold cereal, breads, fruit, meat and cheese slices, fruit juices, and a machine that made several types of coffee.The best selling point of Hotel Atlas is its location right in the heart of the Gothic Quarter, the heart of Barcelona. The area has countless pedestrian friendly walkway, especially a street called The Ramblas, filled with cafes and shops. The Mercat de la Boqueria, a covered food market filled with vendors hawking everything from fruit juices to meats, fish and wine is two blocks away. There is an internet cafe just around the corner, and the beach is an enjoyable 25 minute stroll from the hotel. The Liceu subway stop is within 200 feet and the Plaza Catalunya where one can catch the tour buses is a ten minute walk. While we were warned to be wary of pickpockets, we felt safe walking back to the hotel even at midnight.Hotel Atlas is not the Four Seasons, but at 70 Euros a night vs. 400+ a night for the Four Seasons, it is a great value for the money. 
